				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${y}_{i}=\varphi \left(e\right)=\varphi \left(\sum_{j=1}^{N}{w}_{ij}{x}_{j}+B\right)$$\end{document}where xj (j = 1, 2, …, N) are the inputs, yi is the output, e is the neurons net value, wij is the weight for each input j, B is the bias, and φ is the neuron’s activation function.Fig. 8
Model of artificial neuron

The numerical tests have shown that the response of the sensor is dependent of the previous states of the sensor. For this reason, nonlinear autoregressive network with exogenous inputs (NARX) was applied as the predictor. If Y(t) denotes the output of a neural network, where t is a set of discrete time steps (t = 0, 1, 2,...), the operation principle of one-step ahead NARX could be described by the following nonlinear function F:2Yt+1=FYt,Yt-1,⋯,Yt-dy,ut,ut-1,⋯,u(t-du)\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$Y\left(t+1\right)=F\left(Y\left(t\right),Y\left(t-1\right),\dots ,Y\left(t-{d}_{y}\right), u\left(t\right),u\left(t-1\right),\dots ,u(t-{d}_{u})\right)$$\end{document}where u(t) is the input to the network at time t, and du and dy are the lags of the input and output, respectively.
